    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the first step in picking stocks?</summary>
        <p>The first step is determining your investment goals, risk tolerance, and time horizon before analyzing any specific companies.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Should I focus on technical or fundamental analysis?</summary>
        <p>For long-term investing, fundamental analysis (studying financials, leadership, and competitive advantage) is generally preferred over short-term technical analysis.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How do I evaluate a company's financial health?</summary>
        <p>Look at key financial statements: the income statement (for profitability), the balance sheet (for debt levels), and the cash flow statement (to see actual cash generated).</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What role does valuation play in picking stocks?</summary>
        <p>Valuation helps you determine if a stock is cheap or expensive relative to its earnings or assets. Buying a great company at a bad price can still lead to poor returns.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is it better to pick individual stocks or buy index funds?</summary>
        <p>For most casual investors, broad index funds offer better risk-adjusted returns with less effort. Picking individual stocks requires significant time, research, and expertise.</p>
      </details>
